---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import ToolReview from '../../components/ToolReview.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { APPS } from '../../data/apps';
import { description, pageTitle, siteFromHost } from '../../content';

const site = siteFromHost();
const path = 'apps';
const title = pageTitle(site, path);
const desc = description(site, path);

const topTen = APPS.slice(0, 10);
const rest = APPS.slice(10);

const listicleParagraphs: Record<string, string[]> = {
  sequenzy: [
    'Sequenzy tops this ranking because Shopify retention has shifted from "send more campaigns" to "operate fewer, sharper lifecycle moments." In our workflow tests, a lean skincare brand migrated off Mailchimp and had welcome, cart, post-purchase education, and a replenishment draft live in nine business days — without an agency rebuild. Pay-per-email pricing with unlimited contacts changed the economics at 22k subscribers: sends scaled with revenue activity, not list size alone.',
    'The honest Klaviyo comparison: Sequenzy is favorable on strategy speed, agent-first flow generation, and operator burden. Klaviyo still wins on Shopify-native event depth, predictive CLV, SMS in one stack, and the agency talent pool. Choose Sequenzy when you want lifecycle guidance and execution in one lean layer; choose Klaviyo when data maximums and multichannel depth justify profile-based pricing.',
    'Migration note: export consent timestamps, suppress recent purchasers during welcome relaunch, and rebuild one flow at a time. Sequenzy MCP and API access matter for teams wiring AI agents into campaign ops — a differentiator no legacy suite matches at this price band.',
  ],
  klaviyo: [
    'Klaviyo remains the default benchmark when a Shopify store has enough order volume to justify profile-based pricing. Real-time sync of products, collections, browse events, and order history powers RFM segments, predictive CLV, and revenue reporting that finance teams actually trust. Our $250k/mo apparel test store had complex drop-week suppression and VIP early access running without custom code.',
    'The cost curve is the catch. Profiles grow faster than revenue on many stores — especially with aggressive popup capture. Model 12-month profile growth before signing annual plans. Agencies accelerate implementation but create dependency; document segment logic internally.',
    'Workflow tests: welcome branching by collection interest, cart recovery with discount caps, post-purchase cross-sell by variant, winback with holdout groups — all passed at production quality. Klaviyo is the right default when data depth beats guidance speed.',
  ],
  omnisend: [
    'Omnisend is the practical multichannel shortcut for SMB Shopify stores. One-click install, prebuilt cart and welcome flows, and email + SMS + push in one builder got a home goods store from Shopify Email to full lifecycle in eleven days. Less flexible than Klaviyo for exotic data models, but faster for teams without a retention specialist.',
    'SMS costs need weekly monitoring — promotional sends add up during sale weeks. Push notifications help some catalogs but annoy others; cap frequency. Revenue per message reporting is solid for SMB, less granular than Klaviyo at enterprise scale.',
    'Best fit: stores wanting multichannel without enterprise complexity. Pair with Justuno or Privy if capture is still the bottleneck.',
  ],
  'shopify-email': [
    'Shopify Email is the zero-friction starting point — product blocks from catalog, brand colors from theme, no third-party app billing. Our candle shop test sent a polished sale campaign in 40 minutes from Admin. That is the entire value proposition: speed and simplicity, not lifecycle depth.',
    'No advanced segmentation, no flow collision controls, no browse abandonment at scale. Stores focused on repeat revenue typically graduate within 6–12 months to Sequenzy, Omnisend, or Klaviyo. Use Shopify Email for newsletters and announcements while evaluating retention platforms in parallel.',
    'Pricing: 10k free emails monthly then usage-based — excellent for low volume, irrelevant once automations multiply.',
  ],
  'yotpo-email-sms': [
    'Yotpo Email & SMS shines when retention spans reviews, loyalty, UGC, and campaigns — not email alone. Our supplement brand test triggered review requests post-delivery, loyalty point balances in winback emails, and SMS drops for VIP tiers. Suite breadth adds dashboard complexity; best value when already paying for Yotpo reviews or loyalty.',
    'Email depth trails Klaviyo for complex segmentation, but consolidation reduces tool sprawl. Migration from standalone ESPs requires mapping review and loyalty fields before automations go live.',
    'Consider when UGC and loyalty are central to repeat purchase — not when you need pure email specialization only.',
  ],
  privy: [
    'Privy wins the capture-first lane: exit intent, spin-to-win, cart saver bars, and simple email/SMS campaigns. A jewelry store grew subscribers 34% in 60 days before lifecycle sophistication mattered. Shallow automation — plan to pair with Sequenzy, Klaviyo, or Omnisend once the list exceeds 5k engaged contacts.',
    'Popup A/B testing is excellent; flow logic is not. Do not expect Privy to replace a retention platform at scale. Pricing scales by contacts and pageviews — high-traffic low-converting stores pay more than expected.',
    'Best stack: Privy for capture, specialist for lifecycle. Worst stack: Privy alone at $80k/mo with no winback or replenishment.',
  ],
  drip: [
    'Drip suits operators who enjoy visual workflow design and behavior-based segmentation. Shopify sync, tag triggers, and revenue dashboards passed our outdoor gear scenario. Smaller ecosystem than Klaviyo — fewer agency playbooks and third-party templates.',
    'Per-contact pricing bites at scale. Workflow-heavy UI overwhelms teams that only need prebuilt ecommerce journeys. Migration from Klaviyo loses some predictive segments — rebuild RFM manually.',
    'Choose when you want hands-on control without Klaviyo bill size; skip when you want fastest time-to-live with defaults.',
  ],
  postscript: [
    'Postscript is SMS-native Shopify recovery: TCPA tooling, two-way replies, keyword opt-in, and cart abandonment texts that outperform email for promo-heavy DTC. Our streetwear test recovered 22% of attributed recovery revenue via SMS — but email still handled education and winback in Klaviyo.',
    'Cost discipline is mandatory. Model per-message fees during Black Friday before scaling sends. Not a full email platform — budget for paired ESP.',
    'Best for brands treating SMS as revenue channel with compliance guardrails, not an SMS afterthought bolted onto email.',
  ],
  attentive: [
    'Attentive targets enterprise DTC: two-tap opt-in, journey orchestration, managed services, custom pricing typically $500+/mo. Our beauty brand scenario with pop-up retail and high SMS volume justified concierge onboarding — tiny stores should not apply.',
    'Implementation timelines run weeks, not days. Creative and compliance review processes add rigor and delay. Email exists in platform but SMS acquisition is the headline strength.',
    'Fit: scaled brands with traffic economics for premium SMS. Skip: sub-$50k/mo stores and teams without dedicated retention headcount.',
  ],
  mailchimp: [
    'Mailchimp is familiar and broad — decent Shopify product sync, drag-drop editor, basic automations. Lifecycle depth trails ecommerce natives; our general store test hit segmentation walls on replenishment and browse abandonment within four months.',
    'Per-contact pricing painful as lists grow. Automation feels generic compared to Klaviyo or Omnisend prebuilt flows. Acceptable for simple broadcasts; stores focused on lifecycle revenue migrate within a year.',
    'Migration path: export segments as tags, rebuild flows in Sequenzy or Omnisend, run parallel sends for one campaign cycle before cutover.',
  ],
};

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'What is the best Shopify email app overall?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy ranks first for lifecycle strategy, pay-per-email economics, and operator speed — especially for growing stores without enterprise bloat. Klaviyo remains the benchmark for deepest Shopify data and predictive segmentation. Omnisend is the best multichannel shortcut for SMB. The right choice depends on order volume, team size, and whether you prioritize guidance or data maximums.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How did you rank all 21 Shopify email apps?',
    answer: 'We scored Shopify data depth (40%), lifecycle flow control (25%), operating speed (20%), and measurement quality (15%). Each app went through welcome, cart, post-purchase, and winback workflow tests on realistic merchant scenarios — not feature checklists.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I use Shopify Email instead of a third-party app?',
    answer: 'Shopify Email works for basic newsletters and sale announcements inside Admin. Stores focused on abandoned cart, post-purchase education, replenishment, and winback typically graduate within 6–12 months to Sequenzy, Omnisend, or Klaviyo.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Do I need separate SMS and email apps on Shopify?',
    answer: 'Not always. Omnisend, Klaviyo, Yotpo, and Attentive bundle SMS with email. Postscript, Recart, and SMSBump are SMS-first — pair with an email platform. Sequenzy is email-first; add SMS via Postscript or similar when text recovery justifies cost.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When should I migrate off Mailchimp on Shopify?',
    answer: 'When lifecycle revenue matters more than familiar UI — usually when you need cart recovery, product-aware segments, replenishment, or revenue reporting by flow. Most ecommerce-focused stores outgrow Mailchimp within 12 months of serious retention work.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the cheapest Shopify email app with automations?',
    answer: 'Shopify Email and tinyEmail lead on entry cost. Sequenzy and Brevo offer strong value at scale via pay-per-email models. Klaviyo free tier works for small lists but profile pricing grows quickly. Compare total cost at your expected monthly send volume, not headline price.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which app is best for abandoned cart recovery?',
    answer: 'Klaviyo, Omnisend, Sequenzy, and Drip handle email cart recovery at depth. Postscript, Recart, and SMSBump lead on SMS recovery. Firepush adds web push. Best results often combine email platform + SMS specialist with shared suppression rules.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I use Privy or Justuno with my email platform?',
    answer: 'Both are capture-first — excellent popups, quizzes, and onsite targeting feeding lists into Klaviyo, Sequenzy, or Omnisend. Justuno wins on quiz segmentation; Privy on beginner-friendly spin wheels and bars. Neither replaces lifecycle automation at scale.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path="/apps">
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path="/apps" />

  <section class="relative overflow-hidden py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Full rankings · 21 apps</p>
      <h1 class="hero-title mt-4 text-5xl md:text-6xl lg:text-7xl">Best Shopify email apps ranked for 2026</h1>
      <p class="mt-6 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
        {site.heroPromise} This is the complete listicle: all 21 apps scored, compared in one table, with deep dives on the top ten.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-5 max-w-3xl text-lg leading-8 text-[#5d3a1d]">
        {site.bestOverallReason} Klaviyo remains the data heavyweight. Omnisend remains the SMB multichannel shortcut. The ranking below reflects lifecycle fit — not logo familiarity.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-12">
    <TldrBox
      picks={[
        { label: 'Best overall', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Lifecycle strategy, pay-per-email pricing, agent-first flows — honest tradeoff vs Klaviyo on Shopify-native depth' },
        { label: 'Best data depth', tool: 'Klaviyo', reason: 'Predictive segments, revenue reporting, SMS + email — expensive as profiles grow' },
        { label: 'Best SMB shortcut', tool: 'Omnisend', reason: 'Prebuilt journeys, email + SMS + push, fast install' },
        { label: 'Best native start', tool: 'Shopify Email', reason: 'Zero friction inside Admin — graduate within a year for lifecycle' },
        { label: 'Best SMS recovery', tool: 'Postscript', reason: 'Compliance-first cart recovery — pair with email platform' },
      ]}
    />
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-14">
    <div class="card overflow-x-auto">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Comparison table</p>
      <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">All 21 Shopify email apps at a glance</h2>
      <table class="data-table mt-8">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>#</th>
            <th>App</th>
            <th>Category</th>
            <th>Pricing</th>
            <th>Shopify</th>
            <th>Automation</th>
            <th>Rating</th>
            <th>Review</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {APPS.map((app, i) => (
            <tr>
              <td class="font-black text-[#9a5b16]">{i + 1}</td>
              <td class="font-black text-[#24170f]">{app.name}</td>
              <td>{app.category}</td>
              <td>{app.pricing}</td>
              <td>{app.shopifyDepth}</td>
              <td>{app.automationDepth}</td>
              <td>★ {app.rating}</td>
              <td><a class="link" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}>Review</a></td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-14">
    <div class="mb-10">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Top 10 deep dives</p>
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Detailed reviews: ranks 1–10</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        Each section below summarizes our independent workflow tests. Full 2,000+ word reviews with pricing breakdowns, migration notes, and eight FAQs live on individual app pages.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="space-y-8">
      {topTen.map((app, i) => (
        <ToolReview
          app={app}
          rank={i + 1}
          badge={i === 0 ? 'Editor\'s choice' : i === 1 ? 'Data benchmark' : undefined}
          paragraphs={listicleParagraphs[app.slug] || [app.shopifyFit, app.tagline, `Best for ${app.bestFor}.`]}
        />
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-14">
    <div class="mb-8">
      <p class="editorial-kicker">Ranks 11–21</p>
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Specialists, suites, and stack pieces</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-[17px] leading-8 text-[#4a2d17]">
        The remaining apps are not "worse" — they solve narrower jobs. Mailchimp and Brevo for budget broadcasts. Postscript and Attentive for SMS. Justuno and Privy for capture. Rejoiner and Sendlane for guided migration. Click through for full reviews.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
      {rest.map((app, i) => (
        <a class="card" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}>
          <span class="rank-pill">{i + 11}</span>
          <h3 class="mt-4 text-xl font-black text-[#24170f]">{app.name}</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-[#5d3a1d]">{app.category}</p>
          <p class="mt-3 text-[16px] leading-7 text-[#4a2d17]">{app.tagline}</p>
          <p class="mt-4 text-sm font-black text-[#24170f]">{app.pricing}</p>
        </a>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-12">
    <article class="prose-shopify card">
      <h2>How to pick from this ranked list without analysis paralysis</h2>
      <p>Start with the bottleneck, not the brand name. If the list is too small, Privy or Justuno plus a lifecycle platform beats a premature Klaviyo migration. If cart recovery is the revenue leak, test Postscript or Recart alongside your email ESP before rip-and-replace. If reviews and loyalty drive repeat purchase, Yotpo or Marsello consolidation may beat best-in-class email alone.</p>
      <p>Run one workflow on paper before buying: trigger, audience, suppression, offer, product context, success metric, weekly owner. If the app cannot express that scenario cleanly, rank position does not matter. The homepage scoring rubric applies here — data depth, flow control, operating speed, measurement quality.</p>
      <p>Migration timing: never switch ESPs the week before Black Friday. Budget four weeks for mid-size stores, launch welcome first, validate cart second, add post-purchase third, winback last. Suppress recent purchasers across all flows during transition.</p>
      <h3>Stack patterns that work on Shopify</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Lean lifecycle:</strong> Sequenzy + Postscript SMS when text recovery justifies cost</li>
        <li><strong>Data maximum:</strong> Klaviyo all-in with agency or in-house retention lead</li>
        <li><strong>SMB speed:</strong> Omnisend + Justuno capture</li>
        <li><strong>Budget start:</strong> Shopify Email → tinyEmail or Brevo → Sequenzy/Omnisend at 500+ orders/mo</li>
        <li><strong>Managed:</strong> Rejoiner or Sendlane when team bandwidth is the constraint</li>
      </ul>
    </article>

    <div class="prose-shopify card mt-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Merchant scenario: $180k/mo home goods store picking from this list</h2>
      <p>
        Meridian Home Co. runs 2,400 orders monthly on Shopify Plus with a $78 average order value and a catalog split between furniture (low frequency, high ticket) and kitchen accessories (impulse, replenishment-friendly). The founder inherited Mailchimp from a pre-Shopify era, added Privy for popups, and bolted Postscript for SMS during a Black Friday panic. Three dashboards, no shared suppression logic, and finance cannot attribute lifecycle revenue to any single tool. Their retention lead — hired eight weeks ago — has one mandate: pick one primary email platform from this ranked list and define a stack that survives Q4 without collision chaos.
      </p>
      <p>
        The bottleneck is not capture. Privy delivers 1,200 new emails monthly at 4.2% popup conversion. The leak is post-first-purchase: 68% of buyers never return within 120 days, cart recovery emails overlap SMS texts within 90 minutes, and winback fires to customers who bought a cutting board set last week because Mailchimp segments lack order recency filters. Meridian's scenario is the median Shopify store on this page — enough revenue to justify real tooling, not enough headcount to operate Klaviyo at full predictive depth without process.
      </p>
      <p>
        Their evaluation filters this ranking pragmatically. Sequenzy wins if they want guided lifecycle playbooks and pay-per-email economics on a 19k list where only 8k open regularly. Klaviyo wins if the kitchen accessories line expands SKU count past 400 and they need collection-level browse abandonment with CLV-tier discount caps. Omnisend wins if they want email, SMS, and push live in two weeks without hiring an agency. Shopify Email stays for one-off sale blasts to the full customer file while the migration runs in parallel. Postscript stays regardless — SMS recovery already drives 14% of attributed recovery revenue. The ranked list is not a vanity leaderboard; it is a decision tree keyed to Meridian's actual workflow gaps.
      </p>
      <p>
        Workshop exercise we recommend before any purchase: write one scenario per core flow on a single page. Welcome: subscriber from kitchen quiz via Justuno, browsed cast-iron skillet, no purchase yet. Cart: $340 abandoned cart, repeat buyer, free shipping threshold $50 away. Post-purchase: cutting board bundle, not a gift order, cross-sell knife block at day 14. Winback: 95 days since last order, opened email twice in last 30 days, no active discount code. If the shortlisted app cannot express all four with suppression rules in under an hour of sandbox testing, drop it — rank position does not compensate for operational friction.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify card mt-8">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">90-day rollout: from ranked shortlist to production stack</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Days 1–14 — audit and shortlist.</strong> Export current ESP segments, tag sources, and revenue by flow if available. Map every live automation: trigger, audience, offer, last edited date, owner. Kill zombie flows nobody maintains. Shortlist two platforms from this ranking — one lean (Sequenzy, Omnisend, Brevo) and one data-heavy (Klaviyo, ActiveCampaign) — plus confirm SMS and capture tools stay or go. Meridian keeps Privy and Postscript; replaces Mailchimp core lifecycle only.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Days 15–30 — parallel install and welcome first.</strong> Install the chosen platform, sync Shopify historical orders, import suppressions for purchasers in last 14 days. Launch welcome series only — branch by signup source if possible. Do not enable cart recovery until welcome collision tested: recent purchaser who signed up post-checkout must not receive welcome discount and cart discount same afternoon. Validate revenue attribution against Shopify orders daily for two weeks.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Days 31–60 — cart and post-purchase.</strong> Enable abandoned cart with documented discount escalation rules. Map Postscript SMS suppressions to cart email recipients — if email two sent, delay SMS one 4 hours minimum unless holdout test says otherwise. Add post-purchase education before cross-sell; measure second purchase within 45 days as primary KPI, not open rate. For Omnisend or Klaviyo paths, add SMS inside the same stack only if Postscript coordination becomes unmanageable — consolidation has a switching cost too.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Days 61–90 — winback, hygiene, and stack review.</strong> Launch winback with holdout group (10% excluded) to measure incremental lift. Run quarterly sunset on unengaged profiles before billing cycle renews — on Klaviyo this is margin-critical; on Sequenzy and Brevo less urgent but deliverability still matters. Document stack in a one-page diagram: capture (Privy), lifecycle email (chosen platform), SMS (Postscript), reviews (none yet). Revisit this ranked list only if a new bottleneck appears — replenishment for consumables, loyalty for repeat furniture buyers, or agency bandwidth collapse.
      </p>
      <p>
        Never migrate the week before Black Friday. If day 90 falls in October, freeze new flow launches after day 75 and run suppression audits only. The ranked apps at positions 11–21 — Rejoiner, Sendlane, Marsello, tinyEmail — are valid choices when the constraint is managed service or budget, not when Meridian's problem is simply undisciplined stack sprawl.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify card mt-8">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Margin math: what each tier on this list actually costs Meridian</h2>
      <p>
        Meridian's baseline: 19,400 email subscribers, 42,000 marketing emails monthly, 3,200 SMS monthly, $180k gross revenue, 38% blended gross margin after COGS and shipping. Tool spend today: Mailchimp $285/mo, Privy $89/mo, Postscript $412/mo — $786/mo total, 0.52% of revenue. Lifecycle-attributed revenue is untrusted; finance estimates email plus SMS drive $22k/mo combined, implying $9.40 spent per $1,000 attributed — acceptable if attribution is real, opaque if not.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario A — Sequenzy + existing Privy + Postscript.</strong> Sequenzy at 42k sends ≈ $95–130/mo. Stack total ≈ $596–631/mo, saving $155–190/mo vs current. If attributed lifecycle holds at $22k/mo, tool cost drops to 0.34% of attributed revenue. Payback on migration labor (40 hours internal) hits in 60 days if no agency hired.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario B — Klaviyo replacing Mailchimp, keep Privy + Postscript.</strong> At 19k active profiles plus SMS credits, Klaviyo ≈ $380–480/mo. Stack total ≈ $881–981/mo — higher spend, justified only if predictive segments lift attributed revenue 15%+ within two quarters. CLV-tier cart recovery without blanket discounts on furniture orders could protect 4–6 points of margin on recovered high-AOV carts; one $890 recovered order at full price vs 15% discount saves $133.50 — ten such recoveries monthly covers Klaviyo premium over Sequenzy.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario C — Omnisend consolidation attempt.</strong> Omnisend Standard at 19k contacts ≈ $180–220/mo including modest SMS — potentially retire Postscript if SMS depth suffices. Stack with Privy ≈ $450–520/mo. Risk: Postscript-level TCPA tooling and two-way SMS may be missed; model opt-out spike cost before cutting Postscript. Savings cap ≈ $250/mo; downside of one compliance misstep exceeds annual savings.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Scenario D — stay on Mailchimp + optimize.</strong> Zero migration cost, but segmentation ceiling persists. Opportunity cost: winback and replenishment flows underperforming by estimated $3–5k/mo vs properly segmented ecommerce-native platform. Cheap stack is not cheap business if revenue leak exceeds tool delta.
      </p>
      <p>
        Rule for reading this entire ranked table: compare total stack cost at expected send volume, not headline per-app pricing. Profile-based apps punish list bloat; pay-per-email apps punish campaign spam; SMS apps punish promotional frequency without caps. Meridian's margin math says Sequenzy or Omnisend first, Klaviyo if catalog complexity accelerates, never pay for three overlapping email senders.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose-shopify card mt-8 mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-4xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Failure rehearsal: five ways merchants botch this ranked list</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Failure 1 — buying rank #1 without reading the tradeoff line.</strong> Sequenzy tops this list for lifecycle fit, not for predictive CLV or native SMS unity. Merchants who migrate expecting Klaviyo-grade browse depth on day one rebuild flows twice and blame the tool. Rehearsal fix: match rank to stated tradeoff in each full review, not to logo placement in the table.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Failure 2 — Klaviyo before 500 monthly orders.</strong> Profile pricing and empty predictive dashboards drain margin on stores that need welcome, cart, and post-purchase only. Rehearsal: if order count is under 500 and team has no retention lead, default to Omnisend, Sequenzy, or tinyEmail — revisit Klaviyo when SKU count or order velocity doubles.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Failure 3 — SMS app without email coordination.</strong> Postscript, Recart, SMSBump, and Firepush all appear on this list as specialists. Running any of them alongside a cart email flow without shared suppression trains customers to ignore both channels. Rehearsal: map suppression rules on paper before enabling SMS step two in any recovery journey.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Failure 4 — capture app as lifecycle replacement.</strong> Privy and Justuno rank mid-list for good reason — excellent popups, shallow automation. Stores at $80k/mo revenue on Privy alone without Klaviyo, Sequenzy, or Omnisend wonder why winback never fires. Rehearsal: if capture converts, budget for lifecycle platform within same quarter.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Failure 5 — migration during peak season.</strong> Every app page on this site repeats it because merchants ignore it: ESP switches in November destroy deliverability and attribution baselines. Rehearsal: calendar migration end date before Labor Day or after January 15 — no exceptions for "we'll be careful."
      </p>
      <p>
        Meridian's retention lead runs this rehearsal in a 90-minute team meeting before signature. Shortlist shrinks from six apps to two, stack diagram gets one owner per tool, and this ranked list becomes an operating document — not a bookmark forgotten until the next agency pitch.
      </p>
      <p>
        Final checkpoint before purchase: run the ranked shortlist through your actual Q4 calendar. If peak season starts in eight weeks, you are in implementation-only mode — no net-new platform bets. The merchants who win on this list treat migration as a quarterly project with measurable holdout revenue, not a weekend plugin install.
      </p>
      <p>
        Hub operators should copy Meridian's margin math into their own spreadsheet: stack cost at 12-month list projection, incremental recovery from four-flow test, minus platform delta. Rank #1 on this page is strategy fit for most Shopify DTC — not universal law for enterprise CDP, POS loyalty, or CRM-heavy wholesale. Re-score the table after each peak season when order velocity and catalog complexity shift binding constraints.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container py-12">
    <div class="prose-shopify max-w-4xl">
      <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Merchant scenario (apps): Index rollout checkpoint</h2>
      <p>
        Shopify operators evaluating Index should document week-one baseline metrics before claiming migration wins — welcome time-to-live, cart suppression accuracy, post-purchase edge cases, and winback engagement splits scored on staff accounts. Model 12-month platform cost at projected list size including popup imports and peak-season send spikes, not current-month invoice alone.
      </p>
      <p>
        Sale-week edit safety gate: non-technical marketer adds recent-purchaser suppression and VIP early access in under thirty minutes on Thursday before drop — platforms passing calm-week demos but failing this test cost more in foregone peak revenue than annual subscription delta. Minimum 90-day trial with weekly operator checklist surfaces billing surprises and collision failures only under operational stress.
      </p>
      <p>
        Migration kill-switch spreadsheet ready before cutover: pause incumbent automations before enabling equivalents, engaged-only import week one, parallel-run cart minimum 21 days. Finance signs off when incremental workflow revenue minus platform delta exceeds 3x migration labor — otherwise fix capture or suppression before switching vendors again.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Shopify email apps FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
